00:24:16.073 --> 00:24:18.374
Well. I mean. it's
a very big book.

519
00:24:18.376 --> 00:24:20.109
And I hope it's
an important one.

520
00:24:20.111 --> 00:24:22.111
If I could only
fucking finish it.

521
00:24:22.113 --> 00:24:23.913
Are you having trouble?

522
00:24:23.915 --> 00:24:26.081
No. I'm not having trouble.

523
00:24:26.083 --> 00:24:29.118
I just...

524
00:24:29.120 --> 00:24:31.753
Well. the problem is
I don't have any time.

525
00:24:31.755 --> 00:24:34.523
Between the teaching
and the baby. and...

526
00:24:34.525 --> 00:24:35.958
...I need to do
more research.

527
00:24:35.960 --> 00:24:38.727
I need to go to France
and spend six or eight weeks

528
00:24:38.729 --> 00:24:41.030
and see where he lived. and
he fought. and he fucked and...

529
00:24:41.032 --> 00:24:43.632
So why not go?
Buy a ticket.

530
00:24:43.634 --> 00:24:45.134
I'm sure you could
figure it out.

531
00:24:45.136 --> 00:24:47.236
No. Alison's program
is accelerated.

532
00:24:47.238 --> 00:24:49.138
so she's got courses all summer

533
00:24:49.140 --> 00:24:51.606
and the soonest I can get away
is... I don't even fucking know.

534
00:24:51.608 --> 00:24:52.874
Fifteen months?

535
00:24:52.876 --> 00:24:54.276
That's frustrating.

536
00:24:54.278 --> 00:24:56.444
When I go I need... I need
time to write the thing.

537
00:24:56.446 --> 00:24:58.546
I mean. a book like this.
it takes concentration.

538
00:24:58.548 --> 00:25:00.548
Real focus.
It's not some

539
00:25:00.550 --> 00:25:03.284
piece of pulp you can
pump out in ten weeks.

540
00:25:03.286 --> 00:25:05.519
Like <i>Descent.</i> you mean?

541
00:25:05.521 --> 00:25:07.322
<i>Descent</i> is what it is.

542
00:25:07.324 --> 00:25:09.357
It was... It was...

543
00:25:09.359 --> 00:25:11.625
It was... it did
amazingly well.

544
00:25:11.627 --> 00:25:14.595
But I've known for a while
I wanted to take the next step.

545
00:25:14.597 --> 00:25:18.599
I wanted to do something
bigger with real scope.

546
00:25:18.601 --> 00:25:21.269
Something serious
and significant.

547
00:25:21.271 --> 00:25:24.505
So do you notice
that the words you use

548
00:25:24.507 --> 00:25:28.943
to describe Bradley's life...
"big." "significant." "great"...

549
00:25:28.945 --> 00:25:32.279
you're now using them
to describe your new book.

550
00:25:32.281 --> 00:25:33.614
Well. he's the subject
of the book.

551
00:25:33.616 --> 00:25:35.082
But what I'm interested in

552
00:25:35.084 --> 00:25:37.852
is how this subject relates
to your own life.

553
00:25:37.854 --> 00:25:39.920
In your mind.

554
00:25:41.958 --> 00:25:44.959
I want to know...

555
00:25:44.961 --> 00:25:46.527
I want to know if it's possible.

556
00:25:46.529 --> 00:25:49.797
really possible to be both.

557
00:25:49.799 --> 00:25:51.799
Both?

558
00:25:51.801 --> 00:25:54.502
A good man and a great man.

559
00:25:54.504 --> 00:25:56.169
And by good. you mean?

560
00:25:56.171 --> 00:25:58.606
Well. the way Helen reads
the obituaries. you know.

561
00:25:58.608 --> 00:26:01.008
for long-lasting marriages.

562
00:26:01.010 --> 00:26:02.342
for virtue. basically.

563
00:26:02.344 --> 00:26:05.211
monogamy. partnership. love.

564
00:26:05.213 --> 00:26:08.581
I mean. do the men who
Helen thinks led good lives.

565
00:26:08.583 --> 00:26:10.383
how many of them
also had great lives?

566
00:26:10.385 --> 00:26:13.553
Depends on what you mean
by great.

567
00:26:13.555 --> 00:26:15.688
Would General Bradley
have conquered Normandy

568
00:26:15.690 --> 00:26:16.990
if he'd been home
changing diapers?

569
00:26:19.426 --> 00:26:21.060
I'm serious.

570
00:26:21.062 --> 00:26:22.061
You look at the way
this guy led his life.

571
00:26:22.063 --> 00:26:23.262
He went out in the world

572
00:26:23.264 --> 00:26:24.531
and he followed
his instincts.

573
00:26:24.533 --> 00:26:25.899
and he took
whatever he wanted.

574
00:26:25.901 --> 00:26:27.066
Maybe he was narcissistic.

575
00:26:27.068 --> 00:26:28.234
maybe Mary was unhappy.

576
00:26:28.236 --> 00:26:30.269
but his life had consequence.

577
00:26:30.271 --> 00:26:33.272
He basically won
the war for us.

578
00:26:33.274 --> 00:26:35.374
So do we judge him for
his absence for his family

579
00:26:35.376 --> 00:26:38.243
and his infidelity. or
do we just let that slide.

580
00:26:38.245 --> 00:26:40.712
because what does it matter
at the end?

581
00:26:40.714 --> 00:26:42.548
The guy stopped Hitler.

582
00:26:42.550 --> 00:26:44.850
What does it matter to whom?

583
00:26:44.852 --> 00:26:47.819
There's a certain type of man
that history reveres.

584
00:26:47.821 --> 00:26:49.320
We see it over and over.

585
00:26:49.322 --> 00:26:51.322
Jefferson. Hamilton. Picasso.

586
00:26:51.324 --> 00:26:54.192
Hemingway.
all of them cheaters.

587
00:26:54.194 --> 00:26:56.862
It's like they have
this bald desire.

588
00:26:56.864 --> 00:27:00.566
this... this willingness
to take whatever they want.

589
00:27:00.568 --> 00:27:02.400
that ends up
making them remarkable.

590
00:27:02.402 --> 00:27:05.571
But again. I want to understand
how this connects to you.

591
00:27:05.573 --> 00:27:08.506
What if. I mean. what if?

592
00:27:08.508 --> 00:27:13.077
What if I... What if I have it
in me to be great?

593
00:27:13.079 --> 00:27:15.079
What if the only thing
that separates me

594
00:27:15.081 --> 00:27:17.314
from Ernest Hemingway is
that he never had to choose?

595
00:27:17.316 --> 00:27:20.284
He... He... He just gave
himself permission to do

596
00:27:20.286 --> 00:27:22.553
whatever the fuck he wanted
in the name of his work

597
00:27:22.555 --> 00:27:25.322
and he didn't care
who he made suffer.

598
00:27:25.324 --> 00:27:28.325
And he blew out
his brains at 60.

599
00:27:30.630 --> 00:27:32.663
Well. what does that mean?

600
00:27:32.665 --> 00:27:34.799
You tell me.

601
00:27:34.801 --> 00:27:38.335
It's one minute
to three. Noah.

602
00:27:38.337 --> 00:27:40.170
Is it?

603
00:27:40.172 --> 00:27:41.806
But before we stop.

604
00:27:41.808 --> 00:27:43.307
I'd like to return
to where we were

605
00:27:43.309 --> 00:27:45.275
at the start
of the session.

606
00:27:45.277 --> 00:27:48.378
You have some questions
to answer with Alison.

607
00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:52.149
Are you ready to tell her
your divorce is finalized?

608
00:27:52.151 --> 00:27:54.118
And do you actually

609
00:27:54.120 --> 00:27:56.487
want to move forward
with your second marriage?

610
00:27:59.757 --> 00:28:02.826
I know I want to be
a good husband.

611
00:28:02.828 --> 00:28:05.695
I want to be... I want
to be a good partner

612
00:28:05.697 --> 00:28:08.698
and a good father.

613
00:28:08.700 --> 00:28:11.701
and I love having a family.
um. and a home

614
00:28:11.703 --> 00:28:14.304
and people who depend on me.

615
00:28:14.306 --> 00:28:18.041
but I know that in my gut.

616
00:28:18.043 --> 00:28:20.144
But I also
want to go to France.

617
00:28:20.146 --> 00:28:23.046
and... for two years.

618
00:28:23.048 --> 00:28:27.450
and fuck whoever
and feel alive again.

619
00:28:27.452 --> 00:28:29.352
and write a great novel.

620
00:28:29.354 --> 00:28:31.721
What I do not want

621
00:28:31.723 --> 00:28:33.456
is to be dishonest.

622
00:28:33.458 --> 00:28:36.059
I tried that
and I hate myself for it.

623
00:28:36.061 --> 00:28:38.227
I...if there's one thing
I could change.

624
00:28:38.229 --> 00:28:40.063
I do not want to lie...

625
00:28:40.065 --> 00:28:42.298
...to myself or anyone else.

626
00:28:44.536 --> 00:28:46.903
I think that's
admirable. Noah.

627
00:28:46.905 --> 00:28:48.872
I really do.

628
00:28:48.874 --> 00:28:50.306
And we're at time.

629
00:28:52.409 --> 00:28:54.778
So you're gonna be
in here again with Alison.

630
00:28:54.780 --> 00:28:57.613
but before that. I think

631
00:28:57.615 --> 00:29:00.016
it's worth taking the time

632
00:29:00.018 --> 00:29:01.885
to look beyond Bradley.

633
00:29:01.887 --> 00:29:05.054
beyond Jefferson.
beyond whoever.

634
00:29:05.056 --> 00:29:07.723
To another list.

635
00:29:07.725 --> 00:29:12.027
A list of men
who did remarkable things

636
00:29:12.029 --> 00:29:14.230
and remained loyal partners.

637
00:29:14.232 --> 00:29:18.534
We hear about them less.
but they're out there too.

638
00:29:18.536 --> 00:29:19.935
I know that. of course.

639
00:29:19.937 --> 00:29:22.738
And conversely.
what about the average guys?

640
00:29:22.740 --> 00:29:26.742
The dentists and accountants
who cheat on their wives?

641
00:29:26.744 --> 00:29:30.680
A few of them sit right
where you're sitting.

642
00:29:30.682 --> 00:29:33.516
Every week.

643
00:29:33.518 --> 00:29:35.351
How do they fit
into your theory?

644
00:29:37.554 --> 00:29:39.054
You could be in France
right now

645
00:29:39.056 --> 00:29:40.922
with a sitter
minding Joanie.

646
00:29:40.924 --> 00:29:42.691
And you didn't
have to tell me about

647
00:29:42.693 --> 00:29:45.193
your appointment with Lucy.

648
00:29:45.195 --> 00:29:49.130
And the very fact
that you stayed today.

649
00:29:49.132 --> 00:29:51.899
and that you're struggling

650
00:29:51.901 --> 00:29:54.902
with these issues.

651
00:29:54.904 --> 00:29:58.473
to me. that says volumes
about who you really are.

652
00:30:00.276 --> 00:30:04.779
Great. so who am I?

653
00:30:10.052 --> 00:30:11.686
Thank you for the talk.

654
00:30:11.688 --> 00:30:13.187
Thank you for staying.

655
00:30:32.407 --> 00:30:33.774
Oh. hey.

656
00:30:33.776 --> 00:30:35.909
Hey. I'll take over.

657
00:30:35.911 --> 00:30:37.244
You go study.

658
00:30:37.246 --> 00:30:39.480
No. it's okay.
I'm almost done.

659
00:30:50.925 --> 00:30:53.426
Here you go.

660
00:30:53.428 --> 00:30:56.128
Hey. I'm sorry
about missing therapy.

661
00:30:56.130 --> 00:30:58.230
I...I don't know
how I forgot.

662
00:30:58.232 --> 00:30:59.432
It's all right.

663
00:30:59.434 --> 00:31:01.167
Class stressed me out

664
00:31:01.169 --> 00:31:02.802
reviewing things
I thought I knew.

665
00:31:02.804 --> 00:31:04.937
but then I didn't. and...

666
00:31:04.939 --> 00:31:06.773
It's fine.

667
00:31:06.775 --> 00:31:09.776
Actually good to have
some time on my own.

668
00:31:09.778 --> 00:31:12.645
Got myself all figured out.

669
00:31:12.647 --> 00:31:16.316
Oh. yeah? Do tell.

670
00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:22.021
Maybe later.

671
00:32:00.827 --> 00:32:05.429
All of us are human.

672
00:32:05.431 --> 00:32:10.434
We all want answers
to our questions.

673
00:32:10.436 --> 00:32:14.739
We want endings to our stories.

674
00:32:14.741 --> 00:32:18.977
In 2014 alone
in the United States of America.

675
00:32:18.979 --> 00:32:21.913
884 people were killed

676
00:32:21.915 --> 00:32:24.215
in hit-and-run accidents.

677
00:32:24.217 --> 00:32:28.686
Only one in five of those cases
ended in arrest.

678
00:32:28.688 --> 00:32:32.390
Only 20% of victims' families

679
00:32:32.392 --> 00:32:34.825
got the answers
they were looking for.

680
00:32:34.827 --> 00:32:37.094
Now. this is just the beginning
of our time together.

681
00:32:37.096 --> 00:32:38.896
but I want to ask
something of you.

682
00:32:38.898 --> 00:32:41.899
I want to ask each of you
to consider

683
00:32:41.901 --> 00:32:44.535
the very real possibility.

684
00:32:44.537 --> 00:32:47.237
the 80% possibility

685
00:32:47.239 --> 00:32:50.140
that whomever
hit Scott Lockhart that night

686
00:32:50.142 --> 00:32:52.542
and heartlessly
kept on driving.

687
00:32:52.544 --> 00:32:57.047
might not be
in this courtroom today.

688
00:32:57.049 --> 00:32:59.849
In the coming days and weeks.

689
00:32:59.851 --> 00:33:02.052
we are going to learn
a great deal

690
00:33:02.054 --> 00:33:05.255
about the troubled life
of Scott Lockhart.

691
00:33:05.257 --> 00:33:07.791
The customers to whom
he sold cocaine.

692
00:33:07.793 --> 00:33:11.328
the suppliers from whom
he bought that cocaine.

693
00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:15.065
and also about
the many. many women

694
00:33:15.067 --> 00:33:18.135
with which he had...
shall we say.

695
00:33:18.137 --> 00:33:21.305
brief entanglements.

696
00:33:21.307 --> 00:33:25.075
Scotty's own brother. Cole.
married one of these women

697
00:33:25.077 --> 00:33:27.076
at a wedding which took place

698
00:33:27.078 --> 00:33:31.080
the very same night
that Scotty died.

699
00:33:31.082 --> 00:33:34.317
Now. the prosecution
will try to convince you

700
00:33:34.319 --> 00:33:38.455
that this couldn't possibly
have been an accident.

701
00:33:38.457 --> 00:33:42.725
Well. there were
many. many people

702
00:33:42.727 --> 00:33:45.829
who had palpable tensions
with Scott Lockhart.

703
00:33:45.831 --> 00:33:48.431
Many. many people
who had motives

704
00:33:48.433 --> 00:33:51.601
far more realistic than those
assigned to my client.

705
00:33:51.603 --> 00:33:54.303
I want you to just
take note of the crowd

706
00:33:54.305 --> 00:33:56.639
outside this courtroom today.

707
00:33:56.641 --> 00:34:00.242
My client is what we call
a scapegoat.

708
00:34:00.244 --> 00:34:02.178
skewered by a community

709
00:34:02.180 --> 00:34:03.812
who doesn't like
what he wrote about them.

710
00:34:03.814 --> 00:34:05.214
The callous outsider.

711
00:34:05.216 --> 00:34:07.316
The unscrupulous author.

712
00:34:07.318 --> 00:34:10.119
This is a man of fiction.

713
00:34:10.121 --> 00:34:12.621
Someone easy
to point fingers at

714
00:34:12.623 --> 00:34:16.325
when you're searching
for a villain.

715
00:34:16.327 --> 00:34:18.827
Yet this character.

716
00:34:18.829 --> 00:34:21.563
bears absolutely
no resemblance

717
00:34:21.565 --> 00:34:26.202
to the person
sitting next to me.

718
00:34:26.204 --> 00:34:29.105
someone who you will
come to know

719
00:34:29.107 --> 00:34:32.674
as a devoted father.
committed husband.

720
00:34:32.676 --> 00:34:35.276
a hard-working
teacher and writer.

721
00:34:35.278 --> 00:34:37.512
and someone who is

722
00:34:37.514 --> 00:34:40.648
incapable of murder.

723
00:34:40.650 --> 00:34:43.051
And someone who.

724
00:34:43.053 --> 00:34:46.488
at his very essence.

725
00:34:46.490 --> 00:34:50.125
is a good man.

726
00:34:53.362 --> 00:34:56.356
_

727
00:35:25.026 --> 00:35:27.127
Shh.

728
00:35:46.681 --> 00:35:48.381
She go back down?

729
00:35:48.383 --> 00:35:50.916
Thank God.

730
00:35:50.918 --> 00:35:52.418
Next time it's you.

731
00:35:52.420 --> 00:35:54.220
She doesn't want me.

732
00:35:54.222 --> 00:35:55.421
She wants her Mama.

733
00:35:55.423 --> 00:35:57.523
Shh. sleep.

734
00:35:57.525 --> 00:35:59.459
Mmm.

735
00:36:27.921 --> 00:36:29.687
Hmm.

736
00:36:29.689 --> 00:36:31.323
You have to invest ATP

737
00:36:31.325 --> 00:36:33.158
in the beginning.
in order to gain ATP

738
00:36:33.160 --> 00:36:34.593
towards the end.

739
00:36:34.595 --> 00:36:38.029
At Step 7 is where
the pay off begins.

740
00:36:38.031 --> 00:36:41.633
In this stage. you gain
back the two ATPs.

741
00:36:41.635 --> 00:36:44.102
the metabolic energy
you spent earlier.

742
00:36:44.104 --> 00:36:46.605
The two units of
1.3-bisphosphoglycerate

743
00:36:46.607 --> 00:36:49.107
we receive in Step 6.
are now converted

744
00:36:49.109 --> 00:36:52.477
into two units of
3-phosphoglycerate.

745
00:36:52.479 --> 00:36:53.778
This reaction
is catalyzed...

746
00:36:53.780 --> 00:36:55.780
Oh. shit. sorry.

747
00:36:55.782 --> 00:36:57.982
...by phosphoglycerate
kinase.

748
00:36:57.984 --> 00:37:00.618
For those of you now having
mild panic attacks.

749
00:37:00.620 --> 00:37:02.486
a friendly reminder:
because of the switch

750
00:37:02.488 --> 00:37:05.922
